Additionally, the growing popularity of glycols in the cosmetics and personal care industry is also contributing to market expansion. Glycols are widely used in skincare products, hair care products, and cosmetics due to their moisturizing and solvent properties. With the rising demand for natural and organic cosmetics, manufacturers are incorporating glycols derived from natural sources to meet consumer preferences for clean beauty products. This trend is expected to drive the growth of glycols in the cosmetics industry, presenting lucrative opportunities for market players to innovate and develop sustainable glycol solutions for the cosmetics market.

Moreover, the pharmaceutical industry is another key sector driving the demand for glycols. Ethylene glycol and propylene glycol are commonly used in pharmaceutical formulations as solvents, preservatives, and viscosity modifiers. With the increasing prevalence of chronic diseases and the growing pharmaceutical manufacturing sector globally, the demand for glycols in the pharmaceutical industry is expected to witness significant growth. Market players are focusing on developing high-quality glycols that meet the stringent requirements of the pharmaceutical industry in terms of purity, stability, and safety.

Furthermore, the automotive industry remains a major consumer of glycols, especially in the production of engine coolants and antifreeze fluids. As the automotive sector continues to witness technological advancements and the shift towards electric vehicles, the demand for high-performance glycols for thermal management applications is expected to increase. Market players are investing in research to develop advanced glycol formulations that meet the evolving needs of the automotive industry, such as thermal stability, corrosion resistance, and environmental friendliness.

